ğŸ“Œ What is Binary Search?

Binary Search is an efficient searching technique that works on sorted arrays. It repeatedly divides the search space into half until it finds the target.





ğŸ”¹ Example:

Imagine searching for a word in a dictionary ğŸ“–. You donâ€™t check every word one by one. Instead, you open the middle, compare, and move left or right accordingly.







ğŸ› ï¸ Binary Search in JavaScript

function BinarySearch(array, target) {

    let leftIndex = 0;

    let rightIndex = array.length - 1;

    while (leftIndex <= rightIndex) {

        let middleIndex = Math.floor((leftIndex + rightIndex) / 2);

        console.log('middleIndex:', middleIndex);

        if (target === array[middleIndex]) {

            return middleIndex;  // Target found

        }

        if (target < array[middleIndex]) {

            rightIndex = middleIndex - 1;  // Search in left half

        } else {

            leftIndex = middleIndex + 1;  // Search in right half

        }

    }

    return -1;  // Target not found

}

console.log(BinarySearch([-2, 10, 18, 25, 30, 40], 25)); // Output: 3







ğŸ§ How Does This Work? (Step-by-Step Example)

For array = [-2, 10, 18, 25, 30, 40] and target = 25:

 1ï¸âƒ£ Find the middle â†’ (0 + 5) / 2 = 2 â†’ array[2] = 18 (not 25)

 2ï¸âƒ£ Since 25 > 18, search right half (index 3 to 5)

 3ï¸âƒ£ New middle â†’ (3 + 5) / 2 = 4 â†’ array[4] = 30 (not 25)

 4ï¸âƒ£ Since 25 < 30, search left half (index 3)

 5ï¸âƒ£ array[3] = 25 âœ… Found! Returns index 3







â³ Understanding Time Complexity

ğŸ”¹ Worst Case: O(log n) â€“ With each step, we eliminate half the elements.

ğŸ”¹ Best Case: O(1) â€“ If the middle element is the target.

ğŸ’¡ Binary Search is much faster than Linear Search for large datasets!







ğŸ’¡ Key Takeaways

âœ” Works only on sorted arrays.

âœ” More efficient than Linear Search (O(n)).

âœ” Reduces search space by half each time (O(log n)).





Binary Search is a must-know for every developer! ğŸš€





